[{"id":40573,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Vm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>, directed along positive <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Vm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>, directed along negative <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Vm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>, directed along negative <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Vm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>, directed along positive <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis."],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Electric potential&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>Electric potential and electric field are related as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>x</mi></math>.</p><p>At the point&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>,&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Thus, electric field is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;along negative <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>&#8208;</mo></math> axis.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40490,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned}\nF_e & =\\frac{k q_1 q_2}{r^2} \\\\\nF_g & =\\frac{G m_1 m_2}{r^2} \\\\\n\\frac{F_e}{F_g} & =\\frac{k q_1 q_2}{G m_1 m_2} \\\\\n& =\\frac{9 \\times 10^9 \\times 6.67 \\times 10^{-19} \\times 9.6 \\times 10^{-10}}{6.67 \\times 10^{-11} \\times 19.2 \\times 10^{-27} \\times 9 \\times 10^{-27}} \\\\\n& =\\frac{10^{-20}}{2 \\times 10^{-65}}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40695,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["$1.8 \\times 10^5 \\mathrm{~V}$ and $-5.625 \\times 10^6 \\mathrm{~V} / \\mathrm{m}$","$0 \\mathrm{~V}$ and $0 \\mathrm{~V} / \\mathrm{m}$","$2.25 \\times 10^5 \\mathrm{~V}$ and $-5.625 \\times 10^6 \\mathrm{~V} / \\mathrm{m}$","$2.25 \\times 10^5 \\mathrm{~V}$ and $0 \\mathrm{~V} / \\mathrm{m}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\mathrm{q}=1 \\mu \\mathrm{C}=1 \\times 10^{-6} \\mathrm{C}$\n$$\n\\mathrm{r}=4 \\mathrm{~cm}=4 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~m}\n$$\nPotential $\\mathrm{V}=\\frac{\\mathrm{kq}}{\\mathrm{r}}$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& =\\frac{9 \\times 10^9 \\times 10^{-6}}{4 \\times 10^{-2}} \\\\\n& =2.25 \\times 10^5 \\mathrm{~V} .\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nInduced electric field $\\mathrm{E}=-\\frac{\\mathrm{kq}}{\\mathrm{r}^2}$\n$$\n=\\frac{9 \\times 10^9 \\times 1 \\times 10^{-6}}{16 \\times 10^{-4}}=-5.625 \\times 10^6 \\mathrm{~V} / \\mathrm{m}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":40655,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>27</mn><mi>F</mi></math>.","<math><mfrac><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>.","<math><mn>3</mn><mi>F</mi></math>.","<math><mn>9</mn><mi>F</mi></math>."],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Electric field intensity at the distance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math>&nbsp;along the perpendicular bisector is<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\" separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>K</mi><mi>P</mi></mrow><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac></math><br /><br />So, force at distance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math> on&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Q</mi></math>,<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Q</mi><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>Q</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>K</mi><mi>P</mi></mrow><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac></mfenced></math> ...<math><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>F</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>Q</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>K</mi><mi>P</mi></mrow><msup><mfenced><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>y</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac></math> ...<math><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Dividing&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math>&nbsp;by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math>, we get,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></mrow><mi>F</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mn>3</mn></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>&#39;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn><mi>F</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40715,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cEvrUMZxHoJajage7slsM988Cl_lcgdIbdkhCsjnnp8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/tRCpITDxeVihau1mb6RKt_1Om7Q5d6n0igfjwHZy05k.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Q5pNS7zdaNOBAV38JSrRgXIn3aXCaq1lsqleHnCfN7k.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aJowl1ePmepPuhEDt9DdsY5OuQFTMbQm5NbMGTCseEE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7QANz4ni6ZG6VcyzksfH6vhJOoJWld1lbkAXMN2x1Os.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":40692,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["Zero","1","$\\frac{144}{25}$","$\\frac{25}{144}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"From question, $\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{x}}=5 \\mathrm{~N} / \\mathrm{kg}$ and $\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{y}}=12 \\mathrm{~N} / \\mathrm{kg}$\nGravitational potential\n$=$ Gravitational field $\\times$ distance\n$\\therefore \\mathrm{V}_{(12 \\mathrm{~m}, 0)}=\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{x}} \\times 12 \\mathrm{~J} / \\mathrm{kg}$\nand $\\mathrm{V}_{(0,5 \\mathrm{~m})}=\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{y}} \\times 5 \\mathrm{~J} / \\mathrm{kg}$\n(Given : potential at the origin is zero)\n$$\n\\therefore \\frac{V_{(12 \\mathrm{~m}, 0)}}{\\mathrm{V}_{(0,5 \\mathrm{~m})}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{x}} \\times 12}{\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{y}} \\times 5}=\\frac{5 \\times 12}{12 \\times 5}=1\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":40434,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The force experienced by the charge in the electric field is given by $\\vec{F} = q\\vec{E}$.<br><br>Given $q = 3$ C and $\\vec{E} = 2x\\hat{i} + 3y^2\\hat{j} + 4\\hat{k}$ N/C, the force is:<br>$\\vec{F} = 3(2x\\hat{i} + 3y^2\\hat{j} + 4\\hat{k}) = 6x\\hat{i} + 9y^2\\hat{j} + 12\\hat{k}$ N<br><br>The work done by the electric field in moving the charge is:<br>$W = \\int \\vec{F} \\cdot d\\vec{r} = \\int_{x_1}^{x_2} F_x dx + \\int_{y_1}^{y_2} F_y dy + \\int_{z_1}^{z_2} F_z dz$<br><br>Substituting the limits from the initial point $(0, -2, -5)$ to the final point $(5, 1, 2)$:<br>$W = \\int_{0}^{5} 6x dx + \\int_{-2}^{1} 9y^2 dy + \\int_{-5}^{2} 12 dz$<br><br>Evaluating each integral separately:<br>$\\int_{0}^{5} 6x dx = \\left[ 3x^2 \\right]_{0}^{5} = 3(5^2 - 0^2) = 75$ J<br><br>$\\int_{-2}^{1} 9y^2 dy = \\left[ 3y^3 \\right]_{-2}^{1} = 3(1^3 - (-2)^3) = 3(1 - (-8)) = 3(9) = 27$ J<br><br>$\\int_{-5}^{2} 12 dz = \\left[ 12z \\right]_{-5}^{2} = 12(2 - (-5)) = 12(7) = 84$ J<br><br>Total work done $W = 75 + 27 + 84 = 186$ J.<br><br>Answer: $186$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40581,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9e5c9397-1c7c-4a9a-858b-152403dee417-e6eae665-9e1f-4be0-868c-2f49ad6d905c-5d4f6ccf-73e4-43b9-996d-09e857a8186f-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 140px;\" /></p><p>Total volume of the drop will remain unchanged,</p><p>So,&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>27</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>r</mi></math></p><p>Potential of the small drops,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>22</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>For bigger drop, potential will be</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>27</mn><mi>q</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfenced></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>198</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40486,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1PblQ3ZoSOlHnQqVJ9OexMcJKkr6UeL1xQSotIwpu6k.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n\nTotal flux through square $=\\frac{\\mathrm{q}}{\\epsilon_0}\\left(\\frac{1}{6}\\right)$\nLets divide square is 8 equal parts.\nFlux is same for each part.\n$\\therefore$ Flux through shaded portion is $\\frac{5}{8}$ (Total flux)\n$=\\frac{5}{8} \\times \\frac{\\mathrm{q}}{\\epsilon_0} \\frac{1}{6}=\\frac{5}{48} \\frac{1}{\\epsilon_0}$\n$\\therefore$ required Ans. is 48","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40471,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["(A) is correct but $(\\mathrm{R})$ is not correct","Both $(\\mathrm{A})$ and $(\\mathrm{R})$ are correct but $(\\mathrm{R})$ is not the correct explanation of (A)","Both (A) and (R) are correct and (R) is the correct explanation of (A)","(A) is not correct but $(\\mathrm{R})$ is correct"],"answer":3,"solution":"A : Since polar dielectrics are randomly oriental $\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{P}}_{\\mathrm{net}}=\\overrightarrow{0}$.<br/>R : If $\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{E}}$ is absent, polar dielectric remain polar \\& are randomly oriented.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40637,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["Surface charge density on the inner surface of the shell is zero everywhere.","Electric field outside the shell is the same as that of a point charge at the centre of the shell.","Surface charge density on the inner surface is uniform and equal to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>(</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>Q</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>.","Surface charge density on the outer surface depends on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\" separators=\"|\"><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>p</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></mfenced><mo>.</mo></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Net charge on dipole is zero, so it will not affect the charge distribution and electric field on the outside but the charge distribution inside the shell will disturbed.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40673,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>32</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>28</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Energy of sphere <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mn>4.5</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>16</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mi>C</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>16</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msub><mrow><mi>&#949;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mi>R</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>16</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msub><mrow><mi>&#949;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>16</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msub><mrow><mi>&#949;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>16</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>mm</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (08 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":40576,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["Both statement-I and statement-II are true.","Both statement-I and statement-II are false.","Statement-I is true but statement-II is false.","Statement-I is false but statement-II is true."],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>If a positive point charge is brought in an electric field. The value of electric field at a point near to the charge may increase or decreases. Hence, statement I is true.</p><p>An electric dipole experiences zero net force in a uniform electric field. Hence, statement II is false.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40487,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["-1.8 J","-2.0 J","-1.5 J","-1.2 J"],"answer":0,"solution":"P.E. of two charges\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{u}=\\frac{1}{4 \\pi \\varepsilon_0} \\frac{\\mathrm{q}_1 \\mathrm{q}_2}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{r}=\\sqrt{\\left(\\mathrm{x}_2-\\mathrm{x}_1\\right)^2+\\left(\\mathrm{y}_2-\\mathrm{y}_1\\right)^2+\\left(\\mathrm{z}_2-\\mathrm{z}_1\\right)^2} \\\\\n& =14 \\mathrm{~cm} \\\\\n& \\therefore \\mathrm{u}=\\frac{9 \\times 10^9 \\times 7 \\times 10^{-6} \\times(-4) \\times 10^{-6}}{14 \\times 10^{-2}} \\\\\n& =-1.8 \\mathrm{~J}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40438,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["$100 \\, V$ and $580 \\, V$","$580 \\, V$ and $100 \\, V$","$60 \\, V$ and $400 \\, V$","$0 \\, V$ and $-200 \\, V$"],"answer":0,"solution":"For the oil droplets to not descend, the upward electric force must balance the downward gravitational force.<br><br>$qE = mg$<br><br>The mass of the oil droplet is given by:<br><br>$m = \\dfrac{4}{3} \\pi r^3 \\rho$<br><br>Substituting the given values $r = 10^{-3}$ m and $\\rho = 1500$ kg/m$^3$:<br><br>$m = \\dfrac{4}{3} \\pi (10^{-3})^3 \\times 1500 = 2 \\pi \\times 10^{-6}$ kg<br><br>The electric field $E$ required is:<br><br>$E = \\dfrac{mg}{q} = \\dfrac{2 \\pi \\times 10^{-6} \\times 10}{5 \\times 10^{-9}} = 4000 \\pi$ V/m<br><br>The potential difference $\\Delta V$ between the plates is:<br><br>$\\Delta V = E \\times d = 4000 \\pi \\times \\left(\\dfrac{12}{\\pi} \\times 10^{-2}\\right) = 480$ V<br><br>Since the charge on the droplet is positive, the electric field must be directed upwards to provide an upward force. Electric field lines point from higher potential to lower potential, so the bottom plate B must be at a higher potential than the top plate A.<br><br>$V_B - V_A = 480$ V<br><br>Checking the given options, $V_A = 100$ V and $V_B = 580$ V satisfies this condition.<br><br>Answer: $100 \\, V$ and $580 \\, V$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40588,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["At <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#956;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> on the right side","At <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#956;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> on the left side of system","At <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#956;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> between two charges","At midpoint between two charges"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/52e5f78e-3d86-4232-9d07-60abe3ac31fa-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 77px;\" /></p><p>Charge should be placed near <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>&#956;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> distance<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cb33023c-f795-4e05-8821-345d9a6be8d2-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 85px;\" /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>K</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>)</mo><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>K</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>)</mo><mi>Q</mi></mrow><msup><mi>X</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>x</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40457,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["$45 \\times 10^{-6}$","$15 \\times 10^{-6}$","0","$30 \\times 10^{-6}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Distance from origin to A: $r_A = \\sqrt{4^2 + 4^2 + 2^2} = 6$ m<br>Distance from origin to B: $r_B = \\sqrt{2^2 + 2^2 + 1^2} = 3$ m<br>Work done: $W = q_2(V_B - V_A) = q_2 \\times \\frac{q_1}{4\\pi\\varepsilon_0}\\left(\\frac{1}{r_B} - \\frac{1}{r_A}\\right)$<br>$= 2 \\times 10^{-6} \\times 9 \\times 10^9 \\times 10^{-8} \\times \\left(\\frac{1}{3} - \\frac{1}{6}\\right)$<br>$= 18 \\times 10^{-5} \\times \\frac{1}{6} = 30 \\times 10^{-6}$ J","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40520,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Ampere – Maxwell law</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>→</mo><mo>∮</mo><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>·</mo><mi>d</mi><mover><mi>l</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>μ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msub><mi>i</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>μ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msub><mi>ε</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><msub><mi>ϕ</mi><mi>E</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Faraday law </p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>→</mo><mo>∮</mo><mover><mi>E</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>·</mo><mi>d</mi><mover><mi>l</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><msub><mi>ϕ</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Gauss’ law for electricity <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>→</mo><mo>∮</mo><mover><mi>E</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>·</mo><mi>d</mi><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>Q</mi><msub><mi>ε</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac></math></p><p>Gauss' law for magnetism <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>→</mo><mo>∮</mo><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>·</mo><mi>d</mi><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40721,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["$32 \\times 10^{-19} \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$","$2.65 \\times 10^6 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$","$7.02 \\times 10^{12} \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$","$1.87 \\times 10^6 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{mv}^2=\\mathrm{eV}$\n$\\mathrm{v}=\\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\mathrm{eV}}{\\mathrm{m}}}=2.65 \\times 10^6 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":40473,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["$\\frac{a}{\\sqrt{2}}$","$\\frac{a}{2}$","a","0"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{E}=\\frac{\\mathrm{KQr}}{\\left(\\mathrm{x}^2+\\mathrm{R}^2\\right)^{3 / 2}} \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{dE}}{\\mathrm{dx}}=0 \\\\ & \\therefore \\mathrm{x}=\\frac{\\mathrm{R}}{\\sqrt{2}}=\\frac{\\sqrt{2} \\mathrm{a}}{\\sqrt{2}}=\\mathrm{a}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40703,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["$8 \\varepsilon_0$","$-4 \\varepsilon_0$","0","$-8 \\varepsilon_0$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Charges reside only on the outer surface of a conductor with cavity.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":40512,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Considering two dipoles with charges <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>q</mi><mo> </mo><mo>&amp;</mo><mo> </mo><mi>q</mi></math>, we can write the equivalent setup as shown below:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c57f78f6-26e2-4447-b6ca-0fdb6d335b5c.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 150px;\"/></p><p>Therefore, net dipole moment is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>q</mi><mi>l</mi></math> in the leftward direction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4f326f6c-3c5f-4122-9eaf-71c7707d2c9f.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 199px;\"/></p><p>Potential required, </p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>K</mi><mover><mi>p</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>·</mo><mover><mi>r</mi><mo>→</mo></mover></mrow><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>9</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>6</mn><mi>q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msup><mn>120</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msup></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><mfenced><mn>27</mn></mfenced><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi></mrow><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mfenced><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>9</mn></msup></math></p><p>Therefore, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40495,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/owamCC5D1zTjcvtp4-0R6OqOhlfdPFA2rb9kPdFkofc.original.fullsize.png\"/>\n$\\begin{aligned} &amp; \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{E}}=2 x \\hat{\\mathrm{i}} \\\\ &amp; \\phi=\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{E}} \\cdot \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{A}}\\end{aligned}$\n$\\begin{aligned} &amp; \\phi_{\\text {in }}=-4 \\times 4=-16 \\mathrm{Nm}^2 / \\mathrm{c} \\\\ &amp; \\phi_{\\text {out }}=8 \\times 4=32 \\mathrm{Nm}^2 / \\mathrm{c} \\\\ &amp; d_{\\text {net }}=\\phi_{\\text {in }+} \\phi_{\\text {out }}=-16+32=16 \\mathrm{Nm}^2 / \\mathrm{c}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40653,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["Electric field of a uniformly charged sphere","Potential of a uniformly charged spherical shell","Potential of a uniformly charged sphere","Electric field of a uniformly charged spherical shell"],"answer":1,"solution":"Electric potential is constant inside a charged spherical shell.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40691,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["reduces by $70.7 \\%$","reduces by $29.3 \\%$","reduces by $9.7 \\%$","reduces by $14.6 \\%$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Electric field intensity at the centre of the disc.\n$$\n\\mathrm{E}=\\frac{\\sigma}{2 \\epsilon_0} \\quad \\text { (given) }\n$$\nElectric field along the axis at any distance $x$ from the centre of the disc\n$$\n\\mathrm{E}^{\\prime}=\\frac{\\sigma}{2 \\epsilon_0}\\left(1-\\frac{\\mathrm{x}}{\\sqrt{\\mathrm{x}^2+\\mathrm{R}^2}}\\right)\n$$\nFrom question, $\\mathrm{x}=\\mathrm{R}$ (radius of disc)\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\therefore \\mathrm{E}^{\\prime} &=\\frac{\\sigma}{2 \\epsilon_0}\\left(1-\\frac{\\mathrm{R}}{\\sqrt{\\mathrm{R}^2+\\mathrm{R}^2}}\\right) \\\\\n&=\\frac{\\sigma}{2 \\epsilon_0}\\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{2} \\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{R}}{\\sqrt{2} \\mathrm{R}}\\right)\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n$$\n=\\frac{4}{14} \\mathrm{E}\n$$\n$\\therefore \\%$ reduction in the value of electric field\n$$\n=\\frac{\\left(E-\\frac{4}{14} E\\right) \\times 100}{E}=\\frac{1000}{14} \\%=70.7 \\%\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":40657,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["<math><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi> </mi></msqrt><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi> </mi><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/853c779e-8b3a-4aa7-9250-45c8e143e529-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 103px;\" /><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math><br /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mi>K</mi><mn>4</mn><mi>q</mi><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>K</mi><mn>2</mn><mi>q</mi><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math><br /><br /><math><msup><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><br /><math><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40524,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>6</mn></msqrt><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The formula to calculate the potential difference between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Q</mi></math> is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>∆</mo><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mi>q</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Now,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><msqrt><mo>(</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>(</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><msqrt><mn>6</mn></msqrt><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>And,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><msqrt><mo>(</mo><msqrt><mn>6</mn></msqrt><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn></msqrt><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><msqrt><mn>6</mn></msqrt><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>6</mn></msqrt><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math> and the value of the charge remains constant, the potential difference between the points is zero.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40601,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8d2ec4b9-60c2-46bb-b6cf-8bbc96eba00a-image.png\" style=\"width: 356px; height: 105px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#956;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>4</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>8</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40474,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["$(4 \\mathrm{~d} / 3,0,0)$","$(\\mathrm{d} / 4,0,0)$","$(3 \\mathrm{~d} / 4,0,0)$","$(\\mathrm{d} / 3,0,0)$"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EUmMu4RcgtNDEvOJCCTkUJrjF12MIvk59VVWSudZl2Y.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>Let $\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{p}}=0$<br/>$\\begin{aligned}<br/>& \\therefore \\frac{\\mathrm{kq}}{\\mathrm{x}^2}=\\frac{\\mathrm{k} 9 \\mathrm{q}}{(\\mathrm{~d}-\\mathrm{x})^2} \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\frac{\\mathrm{~d}-\\mathrm{x}}{\\mathrm{x}}=3 \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{x}=\\frac{\\mathrm{d}}{4}<br/>\\end{aligned}$<br/>$\\therefore$ co-ordinate of P is $\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{d}}{4}, 0,0\\right)$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40671,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["Away from the wire","Towards the wire","Parallel to the wire along the current","Parallel to the wire opposite to the current"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Force on a moving charge,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>F</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mi>q</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>&#215;</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br />Here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8757;</mo><mi>q</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>v</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>&#160;</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>F</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>q</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>v</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>&#215;</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mtext>motion&#160;of</mtext><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi><mtext>&#160;is&#160;towards&#160;the&#160;wire.</mtext></math><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a8f94e4c-3cba-492f-8a8a-6d54c210333f-image.png\" style=\"width: 141px; height: 160px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":40497,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aLlQa_YLaVSo3Xz7UQdUsGIhidpMEPpGpv5LT2yOWas.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\begin{aligned} & \\frac{\\mathrm{Kq}_2}{20} \\cos \\beta=\\frac{\\mathrm{Kq}_3}{25} \\cos \\theta \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{Kq}_2}{20} \\frac{4}{\\sqrt{20}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{Kq}_3}{25} \\frac{4}{\\sqrt{25}} \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{q}_2}{\\mathrm{q}_3}=\\frac{20}{25} \\sqrt{\\frac{20}{25}}=\\frac{8}{5 \\sqrt{\\mathrm{x}}} \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\sqrt{\\mathrm{x}}=\\frac{8 \\times 25 \\sqrt{25}}{5 \\times 20 \\sqrt{20}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{x}=5\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40701,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["$\\frac{1}{4 \\pi \\varepsilon_0} \\frac{(R-r) Q}{\\left(R^2+r^2\\right)}$","$\\frac{1}{4 \\pi \\varepsilon_0} \\frac{(R+r) Q}{2\\left(R^2+r^2\\right)}$","$\\left.\\frac{1}{4 \\pi \\varepsilon_0} \\frac{(R+r) Q}{\\left(R^2+r^2\\right.}\\right)$","$\\frac{1}{4 \\pi \\varepsilon_0} \\frac{(R-r) Q}{2\\left(R^2+r^2\\right)}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Let $q_1$ and $q_2$ be charge on two spheres of radius ' $r$ ' and ' $R$ ' respectively As, $q_1+q_2=\\mathrm{Q}$ and $\\sigma_1=\\sigma_2 \\quad$ [Surface charge density are equal]\n$$\n\\therefore \\frac{q_1}{r \\pi r^2}=\\frac{q_2}{4 \\pi R^2}\n$$\nSo, $q_1=\\frac{Q r^2}{R^2+r^2}$ and $q_2=\\frac{Q R^2}{R^2+r^2}$\nNow, potential, $V=\\frac{1}{4 \\pi \\varepsilon_0}\\left[\\frac{q_1}{r}+\\frac{q_2}{R}\\right]$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& =\\frac{1}{4 \\pi \\varepsilon_0}\\left[\\frac{Q r}{R^2+r^2}+\\frac{Q R}{R^2+r^2}\\right] \\\\\n& =\\frac{Q(R+r)}{R^2+r^2} \\frac{1}{4 \\pi \\varepsilon_0}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null},{"id":40614,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Q</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>512</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>q</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Volume</mi><msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Volume</mi><msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>f</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>512</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>9</mn></msup><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><mn>512</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>128</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40642,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>∝</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>∝</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>∝</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>∝</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"The electric field at <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math> is superposition of the fields due to all four charges. The electric field due to the two <math><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></math> charges is<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0f02fbe5-dd0c-40bb-89a9-e49c9fe96117-image9.png\" /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><msub><mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">cos</mi></mrow><mo>&#8289;</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi></mrow></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><msub><mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">cos</mi></mrow><mo>&#8289;</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi></mrow></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></math><br />The field due to <math><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></math> is towards right and the field due to <math><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></math> is towards left. Also <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>0</mn></math> and <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>0</mn></math> .<br /><math><mo>&#8756;</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&#8776;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8776;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mn>4</mn></msup></mfrac></math><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40541,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electrostatics","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/80b01ebf-0a49-4cae-96fa-58ab289d1933.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 169px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b28714ce-8b98-4533-8f25-96fb07f97c2a.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 159px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4bd0e424-45d8-492a-bb34-866f8372d341.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 167px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/81ec1174-a786-42b4-88ea-0a7e42414368.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 167px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The potential is&nbsp;constant inside the sphere as the electric field is zero inside the sphere. So, the value is given by&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>Q</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msub><mi>&#949;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>R</mi></math></p><p>The potential at the surface is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>Q</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msub><mi>&#949;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>The potential outside the sphere starts decreasing and is given by the formula&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>Q</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msub><mi>&#949;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>R</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null}]